# Branch Workflow

All work follows a strict 3-tier flow:

```
feature/* or bugfix/*  →  dev  →  main
```

## Rules

- `main` is production only. Never commit directly to it. It only receives merges from `dev`.
- `dev` is the integration branch. All feature/bugfix branches merge **here first** — never straight to `main`.
- All new work branches off `dev`, not `main`.
- **Test on `dev`** (e.g. dev Docker on port 3002) after merges. Only when you are satisfied, merge **`dev` → `main`** and deploy — not one feature at a time to `main` unless that feature is the only change on `dev` and you are releasing.

## Starting new work

```bash
git checkout dev && git pull origin dev
git checkout -b feature/your-description
# or
git checkout -b bugfix/your-description
```

## Merging and deploying

```bash
# Merge finished work into dev
git checkout dev && git merge feature/your-description && git push origin dev

# When dev is stable and ready to ship — merge to main and deploy
git checkout main && git merge dev && git push origin main
./deploy.sh   # enforces all checks before rebuilding production
```

## Subagent behaviour

- If the user is on `main` or `dev` and about to make edits, prompt them to create a feature branch first.
- Never merge a feature branch directly into `main` — always route through `dev`.
- Before merging into `dev` or `main`, confirm the dev Docker container has been rebuilt and tested on port 3002.
- `./deploy.sh` is the only approved way to rebuild production. Do not suggest `docker compose up -d --build` directly for production.
